What I Learned
1. Tables

Used to display data in rows and columns
<table> — wraps the entire table
<tr> — table row
<th> — table header cell (bold by default)
<td> — table data cell
<thead> — groups the header rows
<tbody> — groups the body rows
Always use thead and tbody for proper structure


2. Forms

Forms collect information from the user
<form> — wraps all form elements
action attribute — where the form data is sent
method attribute — how it is sent (GET or POST)
GET — data visible in the URL, used for search
POST — data hidden, used for login and signup
Example: <form action="/submit" method="POST">


3. Placeholder

Placeholder is an attribute on input fields
Shows hint text inside the input box
Disappears when the user starts typing
Used to guide the user on what to enter
Example: <input placeholder="Enter your email">
Placeholder is NOT a label — it disappears and is not accessible


4. Label Elements

<label> describes what an input field is for
Always connect a label to its input using for and id
When user clicks the label, the input gets focused
Important for accessibility — screen readers read the label
Example:

<label for="email">Email</label>
<input id="email" type="email">




5. Button

<button> creates a clickable button
Types of buttons:

type="submit" — submits the form (default inside a form)
type="button" — does nothing by default, used with JavaScript
type="reset" — clears all form fields


Always specify the type to avoid unexpected behaviour
Example: <button type="submit">Sign Up</button>


6. Input

<input> is the most used form element
Self-closing tag — no closing tag needed
type attribute controls what kind of input it is
Common types:

type="text" — single line text
type="email" — validates email format
type="password" — hides characters
type="number" — only allows numbers
type="checkbox" — tick box
type="radio" — select one from a group
type="file" — upload a file
type="date" — date picker


Example: <input type="email" id="email" placeholder="Enter email">


7. Name Attribute

name attribute identifies the input when form is submitted
The name becomes the key in the data sent to the server
Without a name attribute the input data is not sent at all
Example: <input type="text" name="username">
When submitted this sends: username=whatever_the_user_typed
Every input inside a form must have a name attribute


Mistakes I Made Today

Used placeholder instead of label thinking they are the same
Forgot to add name attribute on inputs — data was not being sent
Did not specify type on button — caused form to submit unexpectedly

How I Fixed Them

Rule: always use <label> for accessibility, placeholder is just a hint
Rule: every input must have a name attribute or the data is lost
Rule: always write type="button" or type="submit" explicitly on every button

Reflection
Forms are how websites collect data from users — login, signup, search,
checkout. Everything goes through a form. Today I learned that small
things like missing a name attribute or not connecting a label properly
can break the entire form silently. Attention to detail matters even in HTML.
